  abstract = {We have developed the open-source software Tesseroids, a set of command-line programs to perform forward modeling of gravitational fields in spherical coordinates. The software is implemented in the C programming language and uses tesseroids (spherical prisms) for the discretization of the subsurface mass distribution. The gravitational fields of tesseroids are calculated numerically using the Gauss-Legendre quadrature (GLQ). We have improved upon an adaptive discretization algorithm to guarantee the accuracy of the GLQ integration. Our implementation of adaptive discretization uses a ``stack-based'' algorithm instead of recursion to achieve more control over execution errors and corner cases. The algorithm is controlled by a scalar value called the distance-size ratio (DD\ensuremath{<}math overflow="scroll" display="inline"\ensuremath{><}mrow\ensuremath{><}mi\ensuremath{>}D\ensuremath{<}/mi\ensuremath{><}/mrow\ensuremath{><}/math\ensuremath{>}) that determines the accuracy of the integration as well as the computation time. We have determined optimal values of DD\ensuremath{<}math overflow="scroll" display="inline"\ensuremath{><}mrow\ensuremath{><}mi\ensuremath{>}D\ensuremath{<}/mi\ensuremath{><}/mrow\ensuremath{><}/math\ensuremath{>} for the gravitational potential, gravitational acceleration, and gravity gradient tensor by comparing the computed tesseroids effects with those of a homogenous spherical shell. The values required for a maximum relative error of 0.1\% of the shell effects are D=1D=1\ensuremath{<}math overflow="scroll" display="inline"\ensuremath{><}mrow\ensuremath{><}mi\ensuremath{>}D\ensuremath{<}/mi\ensuremath{><}mo\ensuremath{>}=\ensuremath{<}/mo\ensuremath{><}mn\ensuremath{>}1\ensuremath{<}/mn\ensuremath{><}/mrow\ensuremath{><}/math\ensuremath{>} for the gravitational potential, D=1.5D=1.5\ensuremath{<}math overflow="scroll" display="inline"\ensuremath{><}mrow\ensuremath{><}mi\ensuremath{>}D\ensuremath{<}/mi\ensuremath{><}mo\ensuremath{>}=\ensuremath{<}/mo\ensuremath{><}mn\ensuremath{>}1.5\ensuremath{<}/mn\ensuremath{><}/mrow\ensuremath{><}/math\ensuremath{>} for the gravitational acceleration, and D=8D=8\ensuremath{<}math overflow="scroll" display="inline"\ensuremath{><}mrow\ensuremath{><}mi\ensuremath{>}D\ensuremath{<}/mi\ensuremath{><}mo\ensuremath{>}=\ensuremath{<}/mo\ensuremath{><}mn\ensuremath{>}8\ensuremath{<}/mn\ensuremath{><}/mrow\ensuremath{><}/math\ensuremath{>} for the gravity gradients. Contrary to previous assumptions, our results show that the potential and its first and second derivatives require different values of DD\ensuremath{<}math overflow="scroll" display="inline"\ensuremath{><}mrow\ensuremath{><}mi\ensuremath{>}D\ensuremath{<}/mi\ensuremath{><}/mrow\ensuremath{><}/math\ensuremath{>} to achieve the same accuracy. These values were incorporated as defaults in the software.},
